  "created": "2025-10-15",
  "description": "E. coli transports inorganic phosphate via two systems: Pst (high-affinity ABC transporter, Km ~0.4 \u03bcM) and Pit (low-affinity H+ symporter, Km ~25 \u03bcM). Under phosphate starvation, the Pst system is induced via PhoR/PhoB two-component system. PstS periplasmic binding protein captures Pi, delivers to PstCAB transporter. When Pst transports Pi, PhoU inhibits PhoR, turning off PHO regulon. Pit system operates constitutively. Phosphate regulation (PHO regulon) controls ~40 genes for scavenging and alternative phosphate sources.",
  "id": "ecoli_phosphate_transport",
  "keywords": [
    "phosphate transport",
    "Pst system",
    "Pit system",
    "PhoR/PhoB",
    "PhoU",
    "ABC transporter"
  ],
  "lastUpdated": "2025-10-15",
